1) 1 piece Teknic Superbike Race Leathers with matching gloves. These leathers and gloves are about 10 years old. I paid about $1600 for them new. Size 45-56 and gloves are large. They have NEVER been in any type of accident or bad weather (rain or snow) and have always been cleaned and conditioned with leather cleaner after being used. 2) SIDI Vertigo Air Boots, These boots have two riding seasons at the track on them. I paid over $300 for them new. They are in great shape. Size 11.5 US.
3) Arai all mat black full face with air vents and chin spoiler helmet. I bought it new in "02" as a spare/ex-gf helmet. It might have been worn 15 times on 30 minute rides. It didn't spend much time if any strapped on the back. It was always kept at home in it's felt bag when it wasn't used.

Fits perfect under a riding gear and covers all of the spine for full protection. Double-velcro kidney belts are 100% solid and give great support.

I sold my bike when I got back to the states in "07". I had high hopes of getting a new bike but a daughter and then orders to Alaska changed all that. I am pretty firm with the price. You will never find a deal like this again. Call Terry if you're interested @ nine07-7five0-4seven40

title: For Sale/Trade:  Remington collector's item or best hunting rifle- you choose
location: North Davidson County, Winston Salem, North Carolina
postcontent:
I have for sale/trade a Remington 788 with the 18 1/2 inch barrel. This rifle is chambered in 7mm-08 which if you know these guns, you know that is a rare caliber to find. On top is a 4x scope and it has one magazine with it.
If you don't know, the 788s were produced as a "more economical" rifle than the 700s. It turned out that they ended up being tack drivers and were only made for 15 years, (67-83). 
The Remington 788 has two distinguishing design features. The first is the rear-lugged bolt. The bolt has nine lugs in three rows of three lugs each. They lock into the receiver behind the magazine well. Due to this design, the bolt handle lifts only 60 degrees on opening giving more clearance for scopes compared to the 90 degrees required for the Model 700 and other two-lug rifles. The bolt travel is also reduced because of the rear lugs. The bolt pictured is a pre-1975 locking model from a .308 Winchester caliber rifle. The locking bolt requires the safety to be in the "fire" or "off" position in order to rotate the handle and actuate the bolt. Rifles manufactured from 1975 to 1983 have non-locking bolts which can be actuated while the safety is engaged. The second distinguishing feature is the receiver. It has a smaller ejection port than similar bolt action rifles, and no bolt lug raceways. The single stack magazine design yields a smaller feed opening in the bottom of the receiver compared to rifles using a double stack magazine well. When machining of these smaller ports is complete there is more steel remaining in the receiver between the ejection port and adjacent feed port, and significantly more steel overall where all receivers have the least strength. These characteristics combined to make the Remington 788 receiver more rigid and stronger than most, if not all, competing designs, including the Remington 700 which shares the same outside receiver diameter. A rifle's accuracy tends to increase slightly as the rigidity of the receiver increases, as this slightly reduces barrel deflection during firing. Thus the Remington 788 has the structural foundation to be a very accurate rifle.
Pics for serious inquiries only
I know what this rifle is, what it can do and what it's worth. No lowballers and tire kickers.

Guns For Sale - Rare Lew Horton Smith & Wesson -- S&W Model 29-3 .44 Magnum, Round Butt - In The Box   


 Make:  Smith and Wesson 

 Model:  Model 29-3, 

 Year of Manufacture:  1985. This was a special run for Lew Horton (One of 5,000). 

 Caliber:  .44 Magnum 

 Action Type:  Double Action Revolver 

 Markings:  The left side of the barrel is marked "Smith & Wesson". The right side of the barrel is marked "44 Magnum". The right side of the frame has the S & W trademark logo and the "Made in U.S.A. Marcas Registradas" address block. On the frame beneath the arbor is found "ALB### MOD 29-3". 
Barrel Length:  3" 

 Sights / Optics:  The gun is mounted with The front sight is a raised ramp with a red insert. The rear sight is the standard large frame ajustable sight with a white "U". 

 Stock Configuration & Condition:  The stock(s) is/are very nicely grained S & W logo stocks with round butt. There are no nicks dings or losses to the stocks just some minor handling marks. 

 Type of Finish:  Blue, with case hardened hammer and trigger. 

 Finish Originality:  All original. 

 Bore Condition:  The rifling is sharp and deep. There is no apparent erosion. 

 Overall Condition:  This gun retains about 95% of its metal finish. The balance of the finish shows just the beginning of a cylinder drageline, which is barely visible and some general light storage wear. The Screw heads are sharp and undamaged. The markings are clear. Overall, this gun rates in about Ecellent to NIB condition. 

 Mechanics:  The action functions correctly.. 

 Box & Accessories:  The original box is retained along with all of its contents including registration card, Smith and Wesson ammunition flyer, Model 29-3 instructions, warrantee locations, Document from Lew Horton on guns history and options, safety instructions and the original packing paper. 

 Our Assessment:  This is a very special gun. This gun is one of of a limited production run; product code 101224, 3" Round Butt made for Lew Horton in 1985 (See pages 201-203 of the "standard Catalog of Smith and Wesson" by Supica and Nahas), The box matches every detail of the gun including model, serial number, product code, and special order number. title: For Sale/Trade:  Smith & Wesson Model 60 no dash made in 1969
postcontent:
For your consideration is a Smith & Wesson Model 60 no dash revolver in exceptional condition for its age. It was made in 1969, the first year that the Model 60 revolver was numbered in its own serial number range. From 1965 to early in 1969, the Model 60 was numbered in the serial number range of the Chiefs Special line of revolvers. Early in 1969 the Model 60 was given its own serial number range by adding an R prefix. Serial numbers started at R1.

This revolver has no end shake, no rotation issues, no flame cutting, no case marks on the recoil shield, and the timing and lockup are spot on with no play. The bore and cylinder chambers are absolutely pristine. If you're a fan of S&W J-frame revolvers, you won't be disappointed with this one. Sadly, I do not have the box, original grips, original paperwork, VPI paper, or tool kit.

Priced at $550.00 for the revolver alone or $600.00 with a brand new Galco Stinger RH belt holster. Local face to face sale only.
